<leg:level id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.PT6.D9"><leg:level-vrnt leveltype="division" searchtype="LEGISLATION DIVISION" subdoc="false" toc-caption="DIVISION 9 ISSUES ARISING UNDER FOREIGN LAW [rr 6.42&#x2013;6.45]">
<leg:heading><desig searchtype="DIV-NUM"><designum><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.PT6.D9" type="ext"/>DIVISION 9</designum></desig><title searchtype="DIV-TITLE">ISSUES ARISING UNDER FOREIGN LAW [rr 6.42&#x2013;6.45]</title><leg:histnote>
<p><text>[Div 9  insrt Amendment 34 of 2010  Sch 1, effective 25 June 2010]</text></p></leg:histnote></leg:heading>
<leg:levelbody>
<leg:level id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R6-42"><leg:level-vrnt leveltype="rul" searchtype="LEGISLATION RUL" subdoc="true" toc-caption="[r 6.42] r 6.42 Definitions">
<leg:levelinfo>
<leg:levelstatus isrepealed="false" ln.user-displayed="false"/></leg:levelinfo>
<leg:heading inline="true"><edpnum><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R6-42" type="ext"/>[r 6.42]</edpnum><title searchtype="RUL-TITLE">Definitions</title><desig searchtype="RUL-NUM"><designum>6.42</designum></desig></leg:heading>
<leg:levelbody>
<leg:bodytext>
<p><text>In this Division:</text></p>
<deflist><defitem id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R6-42.FOREIGN-COURT"><defterm><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R6-42.FOREIGN-COURT" type="ext"/><emph typestyle="bf">foreign court</emph></defterm><defdesc>
<p><text>means a court of a country other than Australia.</text></p>
</defdesc></defitem></deflist>
<deflist><defitem id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R6-42.FOREIGN-LAW"><defterm><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R6-42.FOREIGN-LAW" type="ext"/><emph typestyle="bf">foreign law</emph></defterm><defdesc>
<p><text>means the law of a country other than Australia.</text></p>
</defdesc></defitem></deflist>
</leg:bodytext>
</leg:levelbody>
</leg:level-vrnt>
</leg:level>
<leg:level id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R6-43"><leg:level-vrnt leveltype="rul" searchtype="LEGISLATION RUL" subdoc="true" toc-caption="[r 6.43] r 6.43 Filing of notices">
<leg:levelinfo>
<leg:levelstatus isrepealed="false" ln.user-displayed="false"/></leg:levelinfo>
<leg:heading inline="true"><edpnum><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R6-43" type="ext"/>[r 6.43]</edpnum><title searchtype="RUL-TITLE">Filing of notices</title><desig searchtype="RUL-NUM"><designum>6.43</designum></desig></leg:heading>
<leg:levelbody>
<leg:level id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R6-43.1"><leg:level-vrnt leveltype="subrul" searchtype="LEGISLATION SUBRUL">
<leg:levelinfo>
<leg:levelstatus isrepealed="false" ln.user-displayed="false"/></leg:levelinfo>
<leg:heading inline="true"><desig><designum><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R6-43.1" type="ext"/>(1)</designum></desig></leg:heading>
<leg:levelbody>
<leg:bodytext>
<p><text>A party who contends that an issue in proceedings in the Supreme Court is governed by foreign law must file and serve on the other parties affected by the issue a notice (a <emph typestyle="bf">foreign law notice</emph>) setting out the relevant principles of foreign law and their application to the issue.</text></p>
</leg:bodytext>
</leg:levelbody>
</leg:level-vrnt>
</leg:level>
<leg:level id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R6-43.2"><leg:level-vrnt leveltype="subrul" searchtype="LEGISLATION SUBRUL">
<leg:levelinfo>
<leg:levelstatus isrepealed="false" ln.user-displayed="false"/></leg:levelinfo>
<leg:heading inline="true"><desig><designum><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R6-43.2" type="ext"/>(2)</designum></desig></leg:heading>
<leg:levelbody>
<leg:bodytext>
<p><text>The foreign law notice must be filed and served by the party contending that an issue is governed by foreign law not more than 6 weeks after the filing by that party of a summons, statement of claim, statement of cross-claim or defence in respect of the proceedings.</text></p>
</leg:bodytext>
</leg:levelbody>
</leg:level-vrnt>
</leg:level>
<leg:level id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R6-43.3"><leg:level-vrnt leveltype="subrul" searchtype="LEGISLATION SUBRUL">
<leg:levelinfo>
<leg:levelstatus isrepealed="false" ln.user-displayed="false"/></leg:levelinfo>
<leg:heading inline="true"><desig><designum><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R6-43.3" type="ext"/>(3)</designum></desig></leg:heading>
<leg:levelbody>
<leg:bodytext>
<p><text>A party on whom a foreign law notice is served who disputes the principles of foreign law or their application must file and serve on the other parties affected by the issue a notice setting out the matter or matters in dispute (a <emph typestyle="bf">notice of dispute as to foreign law</emph>).</text></p>
</leg:bodytext>
</leg:levelbody>
</leg:level-vrnt>
</leg:level>
<leg:level id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R6-43.4"><leg:level-vrnt leveltype="subrul" searchtype="LEGISLATION SUBRUL">
<leg:levelinfo>
<leg:levelstatus isrepealed="false" ln.user-displayed="false"/></leg:levelinfo>
<leg:heading inline="true"><desig><designum><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R6-43.4" type="ext"/>(4)</designum></desig></leg:heading>
<leg:levelbody>
<leg:bodytext>
<p><text>The notice of dispute as to foreign law must be filed and served not more than 8 weeks after the date of service of the foreign law notice.</text></p>
</leg:bodytext>
</leg:levelbody>
</leg:level-vrnt>
</leg:level>
</leg:levelbody>
</leg:level-vrnt>
</leg:level>
<leg:level id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R6-44"><leg:level-vrnt leveltype="rul" searchtype="LEGISLATION RUL" subdoc="true" toc-caption="[r 6.44] r 6.44 Orders">
<leg:levelinfo>
<leg:levelstatus isrepealed="false" ln.user-displayed="false"/></leg:levelinfo>
<leg:heading inline="true"><edpnum><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R6-44" type="ext"/>[r 6.44]</edpnum><title searchtype="RUL-TITLE">Orders</title><desig searchtype="RUL-NUM"><designum>6.44</designum></desig></leg:heading>
<leg:levelbody>
<leg:level id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R6-44.1"><leg:level-vrnt leveltype="subrul" searchtype="LEGISLATION SUBRUL">
<leg:levelinfo>
<leg:levelstatus isrepealed="false" ln.user-displayed="false"/></leg:levelinfo>
<leg:heading inline="true"><desig><designum><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R6-44.1" type="ext"/>(1)</designum></desig></leg:heading>
<leg:levelbody>
<leg:bodytext>
<p><text>The Supreme Court may, on the application of one or more of the parties and with the consent of all of the parties, order that proceedings be commenced in a foreign court in order to answer a question as to the principles of foreign law or as to their application.</text></p>
</leg:bodytext>
</leg:levelbody>
</leg:level-vrnt>
</leg:level>
<leg:level id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R6-44.2"><leg:level-vrnt leveltype="subrul" searchtype="LEGISLATION SUBRUL">
<leg:levelinfo>
<leg:levelstatus isrepealed="false" ln.user-displayed="false"/></leg:levelinfo>
<leg:heading inline="true"><desig><designum><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R6-44.2" type="ext"/>(2)</designum></desig></leg:heading>
<leg:levelbody>
<leg:bodytext>
<p><text>The Supreme Court may, on the application of one or more of the parties or of its own motion, order that the question of foreign law be answered by a referee appointed in accordance with 
<ci:cite searchtype="LEG-REF"><ci:content><remotelink dpsi="05CC" refpt="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.PT20.D3" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID">Division 3</remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>
 of Part 20.</text></p>
</leg:bodytext>
</leg:levelbody>
</leg:level-vrnt>
</leg:level>
<leg:level id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R6-44.3"><leg:level-vrnt leveltype="subrul" searchtype="LEGISLATION SUBRUL">
<leg:levelinfo>
<leg:levelstatus isrepealed="false" ln.user-displayed="false"/></leg:levelinfo>
<leg:heading inline="true"><desig><designum><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R6-44.3" type="ext"/>(3)</designum></desig></leg:heading>
<leg:levelbody>
<leg:bodytext>
<p><text>An order under subrule (1) must:</text></p>
<l><li id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R6-44.3.A"><lilabel><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R6-44.3.A" type="ext"/>(a)</lilabel>
<p><text>state the question of foreign law to be answered, and</text></p>
</li>
<li id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R6-44.3.B"><lilabel><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R6-44.3.B" type="ext"/>(b)</lilabel>
<p><text>state the facts or assumptions upon which the answer to the question is to be determined, and</text></p>
</li>
<li id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R6-44.3.C"><lilabel><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R6-44.3.C" type="ext"/>(c)</lilabel>
<p><text>contain a statement to the effect that the foreign court may vary the facts or assumptions and the question to be answered, and</text></p>
</li>
<li id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R6-44.3.D"><lilabel><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R6-44.3.D" type="ext"/>(d)</lilabel>
<p><text>state whether and to what extent the parties may depart from the facts or assumptions in the determination of the question by the foreign court.</text></p>
</li>
</l>
</leg:bodytext>
</leg:levelbody>
</leg:level-vrnt>
</leg:level>
<leg:level id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R6-44.4"><leg:level-vrnt leveltype="subrul" searchtype="LEGISLATION SUBRUL">
<leg:levelinfo>
<leg:levelstatus isrepealed="false" ln.user-displayed="false"/></leg:levelinfo>
<leg:heading inline="true"><desig><designum><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R6-44.4" type="ext"/>(4)</designum></desig></leg:heading>
<leg:levelbody>
<leg:bodytext>
<p><text>The Supreme Court may give directions for the preparation of a statement as to the nature of the issue out of which the question arises for inclusion with the question to be answered by the foreign court or the referee.</text></p>
</leg:bodytext>
</leg:levelbody>
</leg:level-vrnt>
</leg:level>
<leg:bodytext>
<leg:comntry subdoc="true" toc-caption="NOTE"><heading searchtype="COMMENTARY"><title><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.PT6-R44.COM1" type="ext"/>NOTE</title></heading>
<level id="UCPN_UCPR.SGM_UCPN.UCPR.6-44-5" leveltype="para0" subdoc="true" toc-caption="[6.44.5] Foreign law &#x2014; referral under UCPR r 20.14">
<glp:note><blockquote><hrule/>
<p>
<text><inlineobject attachment="web-server" filename="leg1.gif" type="image"/> Legislation cited in [6.44.5] below. LawNow subscribers click through for daily updates and historical versions.</text><text> </text>
<text>(NSW) <ci:cite searchtype="LEG-REF"><ci:content><remotelink alttext="Click to link to LawNow Legislation" dpsi="005Y" refpt="NSW_ACT_1970-52" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID">Supreme Court Act 1970</remotelink> s 125.</ci:content></ci:cite></text>
<text>(NSW) <ci:cite searchtype="LEG-REF"><ci:content><remotelink alttext="Click to link to LawNow Legislation" dpsi="005Y" refpt="NSW_REG_2005-418" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID">Uniform Civil Procedure Rules 2005</remotelink> r 20.14.</ci:content></ci:cite></text>
</p></blockquote></glp:note><heading searchtype="COMMENTARY"><edpnum><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.6-44-5" type="ext"/>[6.44.5] </edpnum><title>Foreign law &#x2014; referral under UCPR r 20.14</title></heading>
<bodytext searchtype="COMMENTARY">
<p>
<text>The rules in this Division are specifically authorised by 
<ci:cite searchtype="LEG-REF"><ci:content><remotelink dpsi="05CC" refpt="UCPN.SC.SCA70.S125" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID">s 125</remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>
 of the Supreme Court Act 1970. They permit disputed questions of foreign law to be determined, using the reference procedure under UCPR 
<ci:cite searchtype="LEG-REF"><ci:content><remotelink dpsi="05CC" refpt="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R20-14" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID">r 20.14</remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>
, either by lawyers (and even judges) in the relevant foreign jurisdiction: see <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseinfo><ci:decisiondate year="2011"/></ci:caseinfo><ci:caseref ID="cr001106" spanref="cr001106-001"><ci:reporter value="ALR"/><ci:volume num="279"/><ci:page num="737"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref ID="cr001107" spanref="cr001107-002"><ci:reporter value="urj"/><ci:refnum num="BC201101958"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Fleming v Marshall</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr001106-001">(2011) 279 ALR 737</ci:span>; [2011] NSWCA 86; <ci:span spanid="cr001107-002"> BC201101958</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="531777" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite> esp <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseref ID="cr001108" spanref="cr001108-000" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="NSWCA"/><ci:edition><ci:date year="2011"/></ci:edition><ci:pinpoint num="7" targettype="para"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"><ci:span spanid="cr001108-000" status="unval">at [7]&#x2013;[10]</ci:span></citefragment></ci:content></ci:cite>.</text></p>
</bodytext>
</level><level id="UCPN_UCPR.SGM_UCPN.UCPR.6-44-10" leveltype="para0" subdoc="true" toc-caption="[6.44.10] Foreign law &#x2014; arrangements for reciprocal determination"><heading searchtype="COMMENTARY"><edpnum><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.6-44-10" type="ext"/>[6.44.10] </edpnum><title>Foreign law &#x2014; arrangements for reciprocal determination</title></heading>
<bodytext searchtype="COMMENTARY">
<p>
<text>The NSW Supreme Court has reciprocal memoranda of understanding with a number of foreign jurisdictions to facilitate the determination of foreign law questions.  </text></p>
<p>
<text>Each Memorandum of Understanding provides for each local court to give consideration, in accordance with its Rules and procedures, to directing parties to take steps to have any contested issue of foreign law to be determined by the courts of that jurisdiction.  The intention of the Memorandum of Understanding is to overcome the difficulties and costs involved in the ordinary procedures where questions of foreign law are determined as matters of fact in local courts, and are typically resolved on the basis expert evidence. </text></p>
<p>
<text>The following memoranda of understanding have been entered into by the NSW Supreme Court:</text>
<l>
<li>
<lilabel>&#x2022;</lilabel>
<p><text>New York (State): 20 December 2010</text></p></li>
<li>
<lilabel>&#x2022;</lilabel>
<p><text>Singapore: 14 September 2010</text></p></li></l></p>
<p>
<text>Each of these agreements is expressed to continue for 5 years &#x201c;at which time it is anticipated that the procedures herein referred to will be sufficiently well established not to require a succeeding agreement&#x201d;.   The text of the memoranda is set out at 
<remotelink href="www.supremecourt.lawlink.nsw.gov.au/supremecourt/sco2_internationaljudicialcooperation.html" hrefclass="http" newwindow="YES">http://www.supremecourt.lawlink.nsw. gov.au/supremecourt/sco2_internationaljudicialcooperation.html</remotelink>
.</text></p>
</bodytext>
</level></leg:comntry>
</leg:bodytext>
</leg:levelbody>
</leg:level-vrnt>
</leg:level>
<leg:level id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R6-45"><leg:level-vrnt leveltype="rul" searchtype="LEGISLATION RUL" subdoc="true" toc-caption="[r 6.45] r 6.45 Determination of issues arising in foreign court proceedings">
<leg:levelinfo>
<leg:levelstatus isrepealed="false" ln.user-displayed="false"/></leg:levelinfo>
<leg:heading inline="true"><edpnum><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R6-45" type="ext"/>[r 6.45]</edpnum><title searchtype="RUL-TITLE">Determination of issues arising in foreign court proceedings</title><desig searchtype="RUL-NUM"><designum>6.45</designum></desig></leg:heading>
<leg:levelbody>
<leg:bodytext>
<p><text>Proceedings for determination of an issue of Australian law, being an issue with respect to which the Supreme Court may exercise its jurisdiction and which is relevant to an issue in proceedings in a foreign court, may be commenced by summons seeking a declaration of the answer to a question in the form determined by the foreign court.</text></p>
</leg:bodytext>
</leg:levelbody>
</leg:level-vrnt>
</leg:level>
</leg:levelbody>
</leg:level-vrnt>
</leg:level>
</leg:levelbody>
</leg:level-vrnt>
</leg:level></leg:levelbody></leg:level-vrnt></leg:level></leg:body></LEGDOC>